TOPIC: OPERATORS

WHAT ARE OPERATORS?

Operators are symbols used to perform operations on data (values or variables).

Example:
let a = 10;
let b = 5;

a + b = 15

Here:

is an operator
a and b are operands
TYPES OF OPERATORS

Main categories:

Arithmetic Operators
Assignment Operators
Comparison Operators
Logical Operators
Ternary Operator
ARITHMETIC OPERATORS

Used to perform mathematical operations

Operators:

Addition
Subtraction
Multiplication
/ Division
% Modulus (remainder)
** Exponentiation (power)

Example:

let a = 10;
let b = 3;

console.log(a + b); // 13
console.log(a - b); // 7
console.log(a * b); // 30
console.log(a / b); // 3.33
console.log(a % b); // 1
console.log(a ** b); // 1000

INCREMENT & DECREMENT

Increment:
a++ (increase by 1)

Decrement:
a-- (decrease by 1)

Example:

let x = 5;
x++;
console.log(x); // 6

IMPORTANT (Pre vs Post):

let a = 5;

console.log(a++); // 5 (use first, then increase)
console.log(++a); // 7 (increase first, then use)

ASSIGNMENT OPERATORS

Used to assign values

Operators:
= assign
+= add and assign
-= subtract and assign
*= multiply and assign
/= divide and assign
%= modulus and assign
**= power and assign

Example:

let a = 10;

a += 5; // a = 15
a -= 3; // a = 12

COMPARISON OPERATORS

Used to compare values (result is true/false)

Operators:
== equal (value only)
=== equal (value + type)
!= not equal
!== not equal (value + type)

greater than
< less than
= greater or equal
<= less or equal

Example:

console.log(5 == "5"); // true
console.log(5 === "5"); // false

IMPORTANT:

== → loose comparison (type conversion happens)
=== → strict comparison (recommended)

LOGICAL OPERATORS

Used to combine conditions

Operators:

&& AND
|| OR
! NOT

AND (&&)

True only if both are true

Example:

true && true → true
true && false → false

OR (||)

True if at least one is true

Example:

true || false → true

NOT (!)

Reverses value

Example:

!true → false

REAL CODE:

let age = 20;

if (age > 18 && age < 60) {
console.log("Adult");
}

TERNARY OPERATOR

Shortcut for if-else

Syntax:
condition ? true_value : false_value

Example:

let age = 18;

let result = age >= 18 ? "Adult" : "Minor";

console.log(result);

TYPE COERCION (IMPORTANT)

JavaScript automatically converts types

Examples:

"5" + 2 → "52"
"5" - 2 → 3

Explanation:

→ converts to string
→ converts to number
TRUTHY & FALSY VALUES

Falsy values:
false
0
"" (empty string)
null
undefined
NaN

Everything else is truthy

Example:

if ("hello") {
console.log("Runs"); // true
}

SHORT-CIRCUITING

Logical operators stop early

Example:

true || false → true (second not checked)
false && true → false (second not checked)

COMMON MISTAKES
Using == instead of ===
Confusing ++a and a++
Not understanding type coercion
Using operators on wrong data types
